 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/umusemischiefmaker.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Muse Mischiefmaker</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Bored Administrator</span><br>  Posts: 948<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/9/02 1:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=83.topic&index=16>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://members.shaw.ca/sapphirez/images/museaniav.gif width=55 height=176></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Earth and Beyond?</span><hr size=1> Do you think VI invented the fantasy RPG genre with EQ? I'm sure there is tons of shit EQ copied from other previous RPGs, DnD, fantasy genre novels, etc. They didn't make up all those spells off the top of their heads, a lot of it was copied from somewhere.<br>
<br>
I hope SWG lives up to your expectations. I'm already sure I'll enjoy it, at least for a couple of months, but hopefully for longer. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/ushehbahn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>shehbahn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 398<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(10/9/02 2:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=83.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Earth and Beyond?</span><hr size=1> EQ certainly didn't invent that much, but they built sound (well... with the right &quot;Vision&quot; (tm) goggles at least) gameplay mechanics. Those are partially built into the mobs AI, and partially into the tools the players have to act upon their world. I have noticed scores of small problems with E&amp;B, not least of which are tied to completely untested balance and unfinished character evolution. In many ways, E&amp;B is very similar to EQ and the skill tree is almost irrelevant behind the importance of your class.<br>
<br>
What really bugged me ? Well, on the left we have a fantasy game where you play a creature on foot. On the right, we have a sci-fi game where you spend most of your time in a space ship. You would think that both handle rather radically differently. But sadly :<br>
- no y axis<br>
- no collision detection<br>
- inexistant inertia, ship mass<br>
- completely wrong scales / speeds<br>
- almost no positioning strategy during fights<br>
- gravity pull in planetary orbits ?<br>
So you end up with a space ship that handles just about like my horse in EQ (except i can cast while moving here - yay!). Considering what could have been done when you look at gameplay built in some space sims like Independance war... it's a laughable attempt. And I don't buy the &quot;it's for a larger audience&quot; argument either : you don't have to dumb dynamics down for a game to be usable, you need better UI tools. Namely : a navigation map that doesn't suck in 2D, a half decent 3D positioning radar. While on the UI subject, even the inital EQ release UI was better than this... the cargo trade  and chat windows are just an example of how not to do things. Almost as dumb as EQ 4 years ago. Hello RSI.<br>
<br>
Now if you look at the actual fight mechanics, the &quot;classes&quot; in the game are so directly modelled on the EQ cleric / rogue / warrior... that you wonder why they bothered to find different names. Single example : the &quot;snare&quot; device. How about, instead of making a ship &quot;magically&quot; &quot;snared&quot;, you actually had a way of setting your weapons to target specific parts of a ship ? Even 'arcade' style space sims like Wing Commander were taking on account the location of impacts and disabling ship functionalities accordingly. What's the difference ? You open up a whole field of strategic opportunities, you got something that actually feels real and explainable rather than the magic &quot;snare device&quot; that could be named &quot;snare spell&quot;. And I am not even going to go along the lines of what you could do instead of the ridiculous &quot;fear&quot; skill... &quot;Hacking my lasers&quot; bahahaha ! How about we start replacing the idea of a spaceship with an inventory (yay - i won Emperor's reactor !) with the idea of modular ships. Sure, it means that you have more material than 4 pre-designed space ships, but i guess they spent all the money on the Star Wars guy (Doug Chiang) who drew these 4.<br>
<br>
On the trader part of the game : it's not exactly worthless, but there is next to zero market or economy. The system is completely closed off and static. No &quot;supply and demand&quot; to speculate on, just predefined commercial lines. No commercial tax havens either that could have added some serious spice to the mix. Another aspect that's poorly thought out. Even a game like Elite back in the days had a far deeper trading aspect than this. Mankind could have been an example to learn from.<br>
<br>
Oh yeah : space station design... /yawn. They had an inkling of an idea with sort of modular geometry elements, but it kind of fell through half way in the implementation apparently. Result : space stations are dull and boring. If i could save myself the time and not dock and deal with characters over the radio, it would be just as well.<br>
<br>
In short : it looks cute but completely lacks the depth that it could have had. Corny dialogs and half baked &quot;story line&quot; don't make up for poor gameplay that has now been worn out by 4 years of EQ. Not worth $10/month or 3 years of involvement.<br>
<br>
S.<br>
<br>
PS : my DAoC account has expired 2 months after official release and the game has been removed from my HD last january.<br>
